"Dehn M., Buma J.","Modelling future landslide activity based on general circulation models",1999,"Geomorphology","30","1-2",,"175","187",,,10.1016/S0169-555X(99)00053-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033368667&partnerID=40&md5=71a63925f2aa1464d9b834f1c621b41b","Department of Geography, Univ. Bonn, Meckenheimer Al. 166, D., Bonn, Germany; Department of Physical Geography, Univ. Utrecht, P.O. B., Utrecht, Netherlands","Dehn, M., Department of Geography, Univ. Bonn, Meckenheimer Al. 166, D., Bonn, Germany; Buma, J., Department of Physical Geography, Univ. Utrecht, P.O. B., Utrecht, Netherlands","Currently, global warming due to increasing concentrations of CO2 and other greenhouse gases is widely accepted. Climate is an important forcing parameter of landslides and, hence, implications of climate change for landslide activity are of high concern for geomorphological research. The present paper offers a method for assessing climate change impacts on landslide frequency based on general circulation models (GCM). GCM results are downscaled with an empirical-statistical technique to derive local precipitation scenarios. These scenarios are used as input to a simple slope hydrological and stability model. The landslide is defined 'active' if simulated groundwater levels exceed a critical level established with the stability model. Recurrence intervals for landslide activity are obtained by applying a Gumbel regression to the simulated annual maximum groundwater levels. Furthermore, it is shown that indirect climate change impacts as well as changing non-climatic parameters can be important for future landslide frequencies too. The use of three different GCM experiments for the assessment of the activity of a small landslide in SE France did not show a consistent picture of future landslide frequencies. This is due to differences between the GCM experiments but might be enhanced by the limited ability of the applied downscaling technique to carry climate change signals. Finally, some possibilities of improving the approach are outlined and the need for better GCM experiments, which provide the basic input of the approach, is addressed.","Climate change impact; GCM; Landslide modelling; Statistical downscaling","climate change; climate effect; general circulation model; geomorphological response; landslide; modeling",,,,,,"Arnell, N.W., Scenarios for hydrological climate change impact studies (1995) The Role of Water and the Hydrological Cycle in Global Change. NATO ASI Series, pp. 389-407. , H.R. Oliver, & S.A. Oliver. Berlin: Springer; Beniston, M., Climate scenarios for mountain regions. An overview of possible approaches (1994) Mountain Environments in Changing Climates, pp. 136-152. , M. Beniston. London: Routledge; Beniston, M., Douglas, G.F., Impacts of climate change on mountain regions (1996) Climate Change 1995. Impacts, Adaptations and Mitigation of Climate Change: Scientific-Technical Analysis, pp. 191-213. , R.T. Watson, M.C. Zinyowera, R.H. Moss, & D.J. Dokken. Cambridge: Cambridge Univ. Press; Buma, J., Dehn, M., A method for predicting the impact of climatic change on slope stability (1998) Environ. Geol., 35, pp. 190-196; Caris, J., Van Asch, T.W.J., Geophysical, geotechnical and hydrological investigations of a small landslide in the French Alps (1991) Eng. Geol., 31, pp. 249-276; Carter, T., Parry, M., Nishioka, S., Harasawa, H., Technical guidelines for assessing climate change impacts and adaptations (1996) Climate Change 1995. Impacts, Adaptations and Mitigation of Climate Change: Scientific-Technical Analysis, pp. 823-833. , R.T. Watson, M.C. Zinyowera, R.H. Moss, & D.J. Dokken. Cambridge: Cambridge Univ. Press; Collison, A., Hydrological investigations and modelling of Alpine landslides (1996) The Erasmus 94-95 Programme in Geomorphology. Intensive Course in Tyrol (Austria) and Student Mobility, pp. 41-45. , M. Panizza, M. Soldati, D. Barani, & M. Bertacchini. Modena: University of Modena; 